#### Fitting a dose-response model for interaction intervention length and age

In the former visualization, we observed an inverse relationship between intervention duration and BMD outcomes; that is, the effectiveness of BMD appeared to diminish as the intervention period extended. Consequently, we intend to model the dose-response relationships between intervention length and changes in BMD, taking into account the variable of age.

Examining the conditional effects of the interaction term can provide valuable insights into the interplay between these two variables. We will begin by plotting the interaction within the Exercise group, followed by an analysis of the Control group. Our observations indicate that an optimal dosage exists, which significantly varies among different age cohorts.

```{r, message=FALSE, error=FALSE, warning=FALSE, results='hide', echo = FALSE}

model.interaction.1 <- brm(mean_diff | se(md_se) ~ 1 + 
                             s(age_mean, k = 4) + 
                             s(length, k = 4) +
                             (1 | studyID), 
                           bf(mean_diff | se(md_se) ~ age_mean * length, nl = TRUE),
                           data = filter(d_bmd_length, trt != "Control",!is.na(age_mean)),
                           family = gaussian(),
                           prior = prior(normal(0, 2)), 
                           control = list(adapt_delta = 0.99),
                           iter = 4000, warmup = 1000)

model.interaction.1.c <- brm(mean_diff | se(md_se) ~ 1 + 
                             s(age_mean, k = 4) + 
                             s(length, k = 4) +
                             (1 | studyID), 
                           bf(mean_diff | se(md_se) ~ age_mean * length, nl = TRUE),
                           data = filter(d_bmd_length, trt == "Control",!is.na(age_mean)),
                           family = gaussian(),
                           prior = prior(normal(0, 2)), 
                           control = list(adapt_delta = 0.99),
                           iter = 4000, warmup = 1000)

pdf("Supplement 12. Fitting a dose-response model for interaction intervention length and age.pdf")
plot(conditional_effects(model.interaction.1,
                         effects = "length:age_mean",
                         int_conditions = list(age_mean = c(50, 60, 70, 80))),
     line_args = c(alpha = 0.2))
plot(conditional_effects(model.interaction.1.c,
                         effects = "length:age_mean",
                         int_conditions = list(age_mean = c(50, 60, 70, 80))),
     line_args = c(alpha = 0.2))
dev.off()

